                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I will freely admit that I didnt even charm one mob until Kunark came out and I was well over lvl 50.  But one reason I chose to play an enchanter was we had a wide diversity of skills, that you can play your enchanter totally different from another and still be effective.  Until lvl 30, I fear kited with a druid mostly in rathe mtn.  From 30 to 50 I developed my mez skills in lguk and Sol B.  I use to kill the chancellor in LOIO by chain stunning while my pet killed it...which led me to AE groups.  At lvl 50, there were very few other classes that could solo the chancellor in those days...since he was able to heal and had a pet.  I started to charm when PoP came out, when I felt the benefit justified the risk.
<br />

<br />
More and more, the diversity of skills have been taken away either with tagging mobs mez/stun immune....or charm immune.  It seems like EQ wants everyone to play the same way...that if you were creative with your skills, you get punished/nerfed.  The big problems is: no one has yet come out with what an enchanter is suppose to do....class definitions where are you?
<br />

<br />
Even though you are not bugged by the charm changes, you should be.  What if the shoe was on the other foot.  What if they had decided to take mez out of the game...that mez was too overpowering...and basically an enchanter should just slow, buff and nuke?  What if I was a soloer that just charmed and I said "no big deal, I can still charm".  The fact is, that many of us play our enchanters differently...that even though we may not use all the skills of an enchanter....I will defend our abilities even if I dont use them, because one day, they may just nerf the ability that I do use.  I think we <span style="font-weight: bold">ALL</span> need to stand<span style="font-weight: bold"> together </span>here and say<span style="font-weight: bold"> NO</span>.
<br />

<br />
It kind of funny because in EQ II, our class is basically split into 2 classes: ability to mez or the ability to charm....not both.
<br />

<br />
By the way, I use cripple alot.  It is most useful with powerful mobs.  The Overseer in Tactics hits for around 1600 before cripple and around 1100-1200 after cripple.  I also use recant magic alot (I learned to use this because I charm alot of things and noticed how many buffs they alreay had up...also if you have leadership AA, you can see what mobs around you are casting on their friends).
<br />

<br />
Skil</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
